caption.text:
👉 The soft hyphen character in HTML is useful for hinting the browser where inside a long text you might want it to break and insert a hyphen. The hyphen is hidden by default but is displayed only when the word is broken (when there is less space)

⚠️ This is a little different than the word break element <wbr> in that this inserts a hyphen while the word break does not

caption.text:
A common issue when using two stop gradients that are wide apart in the hue space is the gray area in between. This happens because the algorithm to generate in between colors sweeps through the red green and blue values linearly.

🔥 The easiest way to fix this is to add an intermediary color that is in between the two color

caption.text:
Here is a simple trick to add dividers between elements in CSS

We use a combination of two pseudo selectors

👉🏻 The last child selector selects the last item in the element

👉🏻 The not operator negates the last child to select all except the last element

I have also used a logical property which is based on the writing mode instead of border-right

caption.text:
Here is a way to fade out long text that needs to be displayed in a single line - maybe inside a table cell

👉🏻 The trick here is to lay a pseudo element on top of the text and give it a linear gradient from left to right going transparent to a solid colour to give this faded out effect

👉🏻 The pointer events none is used to allow user selecting any text that is directly hidden by the pseudo element

caption.text:
The text-align-last property in CSS is used to set the alignment for the last line of text 

This is very useful when combined with the default text alignment of justify, where we might want to set a different alignment for the last line of text alone

👉🏻 For eg if we have an image as shown here and want the last line to be aligned in a different direction

👉🏻 Or to make sure that the paragraph is not ugly when there are only two or three words and they are justified
